Title: Labour, An Equivocal Concept for Economic Analyses
Author-Name: Ebbe Yndgaard
Author-Email: Eyndgaard@econ.au.dk 
Author-WorkPlace-Name: Department of Economics, University of Aarhus, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Postal: 8000 Aarhus C, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Fax: +45 86 13 63 34
Abstract: Ever since the adoption of the symbiosis of mathematical analytical methods and
marginalism in economics, there has been a tendency of negligence in the sense that it is
seldom to ask the dual question: what are the fundamental assumptions on which the
above approach is resting and are they worth while as measured by realia? In a rather
informal form we try to address some aspects of these basic questions. A main result is
that it is very doubtful to rely too naively on main stream results, relying on a one-
dimensional concept of homogenous labour. Most of the standard results on this
foundation - including those of unemployment - are ambiguous, at best.
Classification-JEL: B4, C0, E1, J3
Keywords: Heterogenous labour, measurement and mathematical representability,
economic methodology
