Title: Investment under Uncertainty - the Case of Repeated Investment Options
Author-Name: Nikolaj Malchow-Moeller and Bo Jellesmark Thorsen
Author-Email: nmalchow@econ.au.dk
Author-WorkPlace-Name: Department of Economics, University of Aarhus, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Postal: 8000 Aarhus C, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Fax: +45 86 13 63 34
Abstract: This paper considers optimal investment behaviour when investment options
evolve deterministically or stochastically over time and investments are irreversible and
indivisible. It extends the standard investment-under-uncertainty set-up with a single
investment option to the case of repeated options. Analytical solutions are derived for the
deterministic case and for the case of a geometric Brownian motion. It is argued that when
investment options are repeated, the simple net-present-value rule in general fares better
as an investment criterion than the rule derived from the single-option approach.
Furthermore, sensitivity analyses reveal that the effects of parameter changes are very
different when using the repeated-options approach instead of the single-option approach.
Classification-JEL: D1, D9, O3, Q12
Keywords: Geometric Brownian motion, indivisibility, investment, irreversibility,
repeated options, replacement, stochastic processes, technology, uncertainty
